{{Infobox artist | honorific_prefix = | name = Seiko Mikami | honorific_suffix = | image = <!-- just the pagename, without the File:/Image: prefix or [[brackets]] --> | image_size = | native_name = | native_name_lang = Ja | birth_name = <!-- only use if different than name --> | birth_date = {{Birth year|1961}} | birth_place = [[Shizuoka, Shizuoka|Shizuoka]], Japan | death_date = {{death date and age|2015|01|02|1961}} | death_place = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | nationality = | education = | alma_mater = [[New York Institute of Technology]] | known_for = | notable_works = | style = | movement = | spouse = | awards = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) --> | elected = | patrons = | memorials = | website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} --> | module = }}
'''Seiko Mikami''' ([[Kanji]]:{{lang|ja|三上 晴子}}) was a Japanese artist known for her large-scale [[interactive art]] installations. Mikami was born in [[Shizuoka, Shizuoka|Shizuoka]], [[Japan]], in 1961, and she stepped into the art scene in the mid-1980s with large-scale art that studied [[information society]] and the human body.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seiko Mikami Project v.1|url=http://www.art-it.asia/u/admin_ed_pics/f4o3H5vQ1VldwERNiL6x/?lang=ja|website=ART iT|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> After moving to the United States in 1991, she studied computer science at the [[New York Institute of Technology]], which lead her art to focus on the interaction between electronics and the human perception.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seiko Mikami|url=http://v2.nl/archive/people/seiko-mikami/|website=V2_|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> She became a professor in the Department of Information Deisgn at [[Tama University]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seiko Mikami Project v.1|url=http://artscape.jp/exhibition/art-flash-news/2015/10115269_19232.html|website=artscape|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> Mikami died from cancer on January 2, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adriaansens|first1=Alex|title=Seiko Mikami|url=http://v2.nl/lab/blog/seiko-mikami-196120132015-1|website=V2_|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>
==Gravicells== Unveiled in 2004, a collaboration between Mikami and the architect Sota Ichikawa resulted in ''Gravicells'', an interactive installation originally housed at the [[Yamaguchi Center for Arts and Media]] (YCAM).<ref>{{cite web|title=Press release: YCAM presents Interactive Art Installation|url=http://www.idd.tamabi.ac.jp/~mikami/Gravity&Resistance/outline2.html|publisher=Tama University|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> The piece serves as a means for encountering the existence of [[gravity]] in a manner one could not experience in his or her daily life, and how the world, our bodies, and our perception are all influenced by gravity in complex and almost delicate ways. When the space is encountered by multiple participants, the visual interactions of the projection between them helps the users achieve a sense of each other. This artwork thus functions as almost an external human sensory function, encouraging awareness of ourselves and others in ways not previously approached.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Spielmann|first1=Yvonne|title=Perceptual-responsive environments: sense and sensibility in Japanese media artist Seiko Mikami’s installations|journal=Journal of Aethsetics and Culture|date=2012|volume= 4|pages=1–13}}</ref>
In the center of the installation space rests a six-by-six-meter paneled floor; these panels are laced with sensors that can detect your weight, tilt, and velocity. This information is continuously collected and analyzed, and is then translated into deformations in the lines projected on the floor near the visitor. [[GPS]] data of the location in which the installation is housed also affects the projected environment and the lines will change according to shifts in the location's gravity.<ref>{{cite web|title=gravicells - gravity and resistance|url=http://www.ntticc.or.jp/en/feature/2008/Openspace2008/Works/gravicells.html|website=Intercommunication Center|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>
==Desire of Codes== One of Mikami's most notable works, ''Desire of Codes'', was commissioned by and created at YCAM.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seiko Mikami|url=http://www.e-flux.com/announcements/37069/seiko-mikami/|website=e-flux|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> Exploring the individual’s existence in public and in private, ''Desire of Codes'' emphasizes the increasingly less blurred line between the individual as defined by information and the individual as flesh and blood.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Takei|first1=Mariko|title=Seiko Mikami|url=http://www.shift.jp.org/en/archives/2010/04/seiko_mikami.html|website=SHIFT|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref> Housed in a space normally devoted to theatrical performances, this interactive piece consists of three parts:
# 90 Wriggling Wall Units: Ninety tentacle-like devices that rotate towards the passerby are placed across a large wall. These devices each have their own camera and microphone, and the data they record is sent to the work’s [[database]], and this information is eventually used in part 3. # 6 Multiperspective Search Arms: Six ‘search arms’ with cameras and projectors hang from the ceiling and follow the movement of the visitors. These arms also record information about the visitors and upload this to the database. Eventually the arms may project enlarged images of the visitor on the floor near visitor themselves. # Compound Eye Detector Screen: Many hexagonal facets are projected onto a circular screen, and each facet contains either one of the video recordings made by a wall unit or surveillance footage taken from various public places around the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=Desire of Codes|url=http://special.ycam.jp/doc/work/index_en.html|publisher=YCAM|accessdate=31 March 2017}}</ref>
In addition to these main three parts, the [[soundscape]] of the area in which the work resides is also altered: the noise generated by visitors as well as the artwork’s own mechanical sounds are mixed and played back, which further emphasizes the indistinction between one's own encoded existence and physical reality.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ross|first1=Christine|title=SPATIAL POLITICS: THE (NON)DESTINATIONS OF AUGMENTED REALITY ART (PART II)|journal=Afterimage|volume= 38 Issue 3|issue=Nov/Dec 2010|pages=16–20}}</ref>
