{{Other uses of|smoking gun|Smoking gun (disambiguation)}} The term "'''smoking gun'''" is a reference to an object or fact that serves as conclusive [[evidence (law)|evidence]] of a [[crime]] or similar act, just short of being caught ''[[in flagrante delicto]]''. "''Smoking gun''" refers to the strongest kind of [[circumstantial evidence]], as opposed to [[direct evidence]]. Direct evidence would include the entire action: Pulling the trigger, firing the gun, and the victim falling.<ref>{{cite book |author=Walton, Douglas |title=Legal Argumentation and Evidence |publisher=Penn State Press |year=2010 |page=78}}</ref>
==Phrase origin== The phrase originally came from the idea that finding a very recently fired (hence smoking) gun on the person of a suspect wanted for shooting someone, which in that situation would be nearly unshakable proof of having committed the crime. The phrase originated in the [[Sherlock Holmes]] story, "[[The Adventure of the Gloria Scott]]" (1893).<ref>{{cite news |last=Safire |first=William |authorlink=William Safire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/26/magazine/the-way-we-live-now-1-26-03-on-language-smoking-gun.html <!-- redirect from http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B07E5DE1130F935A15752C0A9659C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all --> |department=The Way We Live Now |series=On Language |title=Smoking Gun |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=26 January 2003 |accessdate=2015-05-06 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==Extended meaning== In addition to this, its meaning has evolved in uses completely unrelated to criminal activity: for example, scientific evidence that is highly suggestive in favor of a particular hypothesis is sometimes called "smoking gun evidence".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/smoking%20gun |title=Smoking Gun |accessdate=2018-01-30 |website=[[Merriam-Webster.com]] |df=dmy-all}}</ref>
